{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   BENEFICIARY DESIGNATION WARNING — Content Section
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section style="padding: 4rem 2rem; background: var(--surface-container-low);">
  <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <span class="ep-chapter-label">Critical Warning</span>
    <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 3vw, 2.4rem); font-weight: 700; color: var(--primary); line-height: 1.15; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Your Beneficiary Designations Override Your Will</h2>
    <div style="background: var(--surface-container); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; border-left: 4px solid var(--error, #c62828); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--on-surface-variant); margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">
        This is the most common and costly estate planning mistake we see.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--on-surface-variant);">
        Your 401(k), IRA, life insurance, and annuity contracts all pass to whomever is named on the beneficiary designation form — regardless of what your will or trust says. If you named an ex-spouse 20 years ago and never updated it, they will inherit your retirement account. Your current spouse, children, or trust will have no legal claim.
      </p>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--on-surface-variant); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <strong>Accounts with beneficiary designations that override your will:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 2; color: var(--on-surface-variant); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <li>401(k) and 403(b) retirement plans</li>
      <li>Traditional and Roth IRAs</li>
      <li>Life insurance policies</li>
      <li>Annuity contracts</li>
      <li>Transfer-on-death (TOD) brokerage accounts</li>
      <li>Payable-on-death (POD) bank accounts</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--on-surface-variant);">
      We conduct an annual beneficiary audit for every client — reviewing each account to ensure designations are current, consistent with your estate plan, and aligned with your wishes. It takes one outdated form to undo years of careful planning.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   7. FAQ — Editorial accordion
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="ep-faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">Estate Planning FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Learn how to protect your legacy and minimize taxes for your heirs.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Ask About Estate Planning</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Do you draft wills and trusts? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>No, we don't practice law. We coordinate with estate planning attorneys to ensure your legal documents align with your financial strategy. We'll refer you to a qualified attorney and work with them to implement the plan.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Should I convert my IRA to a Roth for my heirs? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Often, yes. Inherited traditional IRAs are now subject to the 10-year rule, which can push heirs into high tax brackets. Converting to a Roth during your lifetime (when you control the timing and tax impact) can save your heirs tens of thousands in taxes. We model this scenario as part of your estate plan.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What's a Qualified Charitable Distribution (QCD)? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>A QCD allows you to donate up to $105,000 per year directly from your IRA to charity (after age 70½). The distribution counts toward your RMD but doesn't increase your taxable income — a powerful strategy for reducing taxes and supporting causes you care about.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I update my estate plan? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Review your estate plan annually and update it after major life events like marriage, divorce, births, deaths, significant asset changes, or moves to a different state. We conduct an annual beneficiary audit for all clients to ensure your designations still match your intentions.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What happens without an estate plan? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Without an estate plan, state law decides who gets your assets, courts appoint guardians for minor children, and your family may face lengthy probate processes and unnecessary taxes. Proper planning ensures your wishes are honored and your loved ones are protected.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Do I need a trust if I have a will? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>A will requires probate — a public, court-supervised process that can take months and cost thousands. A revocable living trust avoids probate entirely, keeps your affairs private, and allows for seamless transfer of assets to your beneficiaries. For most retirees with significant assets, a trust is worth the upfront cost.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How often should I update my estate plan? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Review your estate plan every 3-5 years, or sooner after major life events such as marriage, divorce, birth of a child or grandchild, death of a beneficiary, significant changes in net worth, or moving to a new state. Tax law changes can also necessitate updates.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What happens to my retirement accounts when I die? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Non-spouse beneficiaries must withdraw all inherited retirement account funds within 10 years under the SECURE Act (with required annual distributions for most). A surviving spouse has more flexibility — they can roll the inherited IRA into their own IRA and delay distributions until their own RMD age. Proper beneficiary designations are critical because they override your will.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

